data.content:
## What happened

C# 14 introduces new `Span<T>` / `ReadOnlySpan<T>` overload resolution rules. Your `array.Contains(num)` now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (the span-based overload) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`**. Expression trees cannot represent span-based methods, so the compiled expression throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches pin the call to `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains`, which expression trees support. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays (now resolves to the in-place `Span` version).
